<!-- External Metadata URL: cocoon://metadata/handle/123456789/38/mets.xml?rightsMDTypes=METSRIGHTS-->
<div xmlns:oreatom="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/atom/" xmlns:ore="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/terms/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" class="item-summary-view-metadata">
<h1>Small farms and sustainable rural development for food security in Brazil</h1>
<p class="author-item-view">
<a href="/xmlui/browse?value=Rocha, Cecilia&amp;type=author&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;">Rocha, Cecilia</a>
</p>
<h2>Citation</h2>Rocha, C., Burlandy, L., &amp; Maluf, R. (2012). Small farms and sustainable rural development for food security: The Brazilian experience.  Development Southern Africa, 29(4), 519-529. DOI:10.1080/0376835X.2012.715438 <a href="http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/0376835X.2012.715438">(link to study)
            							</a>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Insights</h2>
<div>
<p>The progress that Brazil has made over the past few years in food and nutrition security has largely been due to the success of its civil society in transmitting its concerns to decision-makers at the policy level.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Policy insights</h2>
<div>
<ul>
<li>It is important to support small farmers in developing countries. Doing so not only increases food security, but also creates employment and sustainable rural development.&#13;<li />Organized civil society should be involved in making, implementing and monitoring policies. Civil society organizations need information, training and education in order to be effective participants in policy development.&#13;<li />Governments need to set up processes whereby civil society’s participation in policy development, implementation and monitoring is institutionalized.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Background/Rationale of the paper</h2>
<div>
<p>The researchers reviewed some of the most important policies and initiatives that have a beneficial impact on sustainable rural development and food security in Brazil. The researchers focused on government programs to help small family farmers, describing the main elements of these programmes and civil society initiatives that pertain to these programs.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Summary</h2>
<div>
<p>Brazil has made significant progress in reducing hunger, and food and nutrition insecurity. By the end of 2009, the country had met the first United Nations Millennium Development Goal of reducing poverty and malnutrition by half, accomplishing this objective six years ahead of the 2015 deadline. Much of this progress has been achieved through innovative policies and initiatives championed by civil society organizations for over two decades.  &#13;<p />Civil society organizations have high levels of participation in Brazil due to the institutionalization of these organisations in local and national level councils.  For example, through their participation on food and nutrition security councils, civil society organizations promote a more integrated perspective on public policy planning and healthy food practices.  As a result of these efforts, Brazil added the “Right to Food” to the country’s constitution in 2010, making it the duty of the state to ensure that all Brazilians enjoy adequate food.</p>
</div>
</div>
<h2>Contact the Ryerson researcher(s)</h2>Cecilia Rocha, Associate Professor, School of Nutrition <a href="&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;mailto:crocha@ryerson.ca">(email)
            								</a>
